  "text": "Fusion of single vesicles produced stepwise changes in membrane capacitance [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . We recorded capacitance in cell-attached patches from wild-type (Fig. 6a) and knockout nerve terminals (Fig. 6b) and saw both upward exocytosis steps and downward endocytosis steps (Fig. 6) . The distributions of step sizes for exocytosis were indistinguishable between wild-type and knockout terminals (Fig. 7a) . Both distributions had two components that corresponded to the microvesicles and DCVs that were seen in electron microscopy. To separate the analysis of microvesicles and DCVs, we divided capacitance steps according to a cutoff value of 80 aF (this value was smaller than that used for rat nerve terminals [CITATION_3] because of the smaller vesicles in mouse). Microvesicle steps averaged 36.0 ± 0.8 aF (n ¼ 452) in wild types and 34.7 ± 0.9 aF (n ¼ 351) in knockouts (P ¼ 0.13). DCV steps averaged 211.6 ± 16.4 aF (n ¼ 186) in wild types and 187.3 ± 16.3 aF (n ¼ 139) in knockouts (P ¼ 0.15; Fig. 7b ). Assuming spherical vesicles and a specific membrane capacitance of 0.9 mF cm -2 (ref. [CITATION_4] , we computed vesicle diameters for each step. Microvesicles had essentially identical diameters, 34.8 ± 0.4 nm and 34.1 ± 0.4 nm for wild types and knockouts, respectively. DCVs had diameters of 81.3 ± 2.2 nm and 76.7 ± 2.3 nm for wild types and knockouts, respectively, which were not as similar as the microvesicle diameters, but were not significantly different (P ¼ 0.12 for microvesicles and P ¼ 0.07 for DCVs).",
